content.problemStatement:
**Nested if** statements allow you to place one if statement inside another. This is useful when you want to check a secondary condition only if the first one is true.

**Syntax**
```cpp
if (condition1) {
    // Code block if condition1 is true

    if (condition2) {
        // Code block if both condition1 and condition2 are true
    } else {
        // Code block if condition1 is true but condition2 is false
    }

} else {
    // Code block if condition1 is false
}
```
---

**Example**
```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int age = 22;
    bool hasTicket = true;

    if (age >= 18) { // Outer condition: age check
        if (hasTicket) { // Inner condition: ticket check
            cout << "Access granted to the concert." << endl;
        } else {
            cout << "Ticket required for entry." << endl;
        }
    } else {
        cout << "You must be 18 or older to attend." << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```
**Expected Output**
```default
Access granted to the concert.
```

